\title{Deeptools}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"NGS analysis toolkit. BAM to bigWig conversion, QC (correlation, PCA, fingerprints), heatmaps/profiles (TSS, peaks), for ChIP-seq, RNA-seq, ATAC-seq visualization."}

\subtree{
\title{deepTools: NGS Data Analysis Toolkit}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{deepTools is a comprehensive suite of Python command-line tools designed for processing and analyzing high-throughput sequencing data. Use deepTools to perform quality control, normalize data, compare samples, and generate publication-quality visualizations for ChIP-seq, RNA-seq, ATAC-seq, MNase-seq, and other NGS experiments.}

\p{\strong{Core capabilities:}}

\ul{
\li{Convert BAM alignments to normalized coverage tracks (bigWig/bedGraph)}
\li{Quality control assessment (fingerprint, correlation, coverage)}
\li{Sample comparison and correlation analysis}
\li{Heatmap and profile plot generation around genomic features}
\li{Enrichment analysis and peak region visualization}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{File conversion}: "Convert BAM to bigWig", "generate coverage tracks", "normalize ChIP-seq data"}
\li{\strong{Quality control}: "check ChIP quality", "compare replicates", "assess sequencing depth", "QC analysis"}
\li{\strong{Visualization}: "create heatmap around TSS", "plot ChIP signal", "visualize enrichment", "generate profile plot"}
\li{\strong{Sample comparison}: "compare treatment vs control", "correlate samples", "PCA analysis"}
\li{\strong{Analysis workflows}: "analyze ChIP-seq data", "RNA-seq coverage", "ATAC-seq analysis", "complete workflow"}
\li{\strong{Working with specific file types}: BAM files, bigWig files, BED region files in genomics context}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\p{For users new to deepTools, start with file validation and common workflows:}

\subtree{
\title{1. Validate Input Files}
\p{Before running any analysis, validate BAM, bigWig, and BED files using the validation script:}

\pre{\startverb
python scripts/validate_files.py --bam sample1.bam sample2.bam --bed regions.bed
\stopverb}

\p{This checks file existence, BAM indices, and format correctness.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Generate Workflow Template}
\p{For standard analyses, use the workflow generator to create customized scripts:}

\pre{\startverb
# List available workflows
python scripts/workflow_generator.py --list

# Generate ChIP-seq QC workflow
python scripts/workflow_generator.py chipseq_qc -o qc_workflow.sh \
    --input-bam Input.bam --chip-bams "ChIP1.bam ChIP2.bam" \
    --genome-size 2913022398

# Make executable and run
chmod +x qc_workflow.sh
./qc_workflow.sh
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Most Common Operations}
\p{See \code{\startverb assets/quick_reference.md\stopverb} for frequently used commands and parameters.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\pre{\startverb
uv pip install deeptools
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Workflows}
\p{deepTools workflows typically follow this pattern: \strong{QC → Normalization → Comparison/Visualization}}

\subtree{
\title{ChIP-seq Quality Control Workflow}
\p{When users request ChIP-seq QC or quality assessment:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Generate workflow script} using \code{\startverb scripts/workflow_generator.py chipseq_qc\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Key QC steps}:}
\li{Sample correlation (multiBamSummary + plotCorrelation)}
\li{PCA analysis (plotPCA)}
\li{Coverage assessment (plotCoverage)}
\li{Fragment size validation (bamPEFragmentSize)}
\li{ChIP enrichment strength (plotFingerprint)}
}

\p{\strong{Interpreting results:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Correlation}: Replicates should cluster together with high correlation (>0.9)}
\li{\strong{Fingerprint}: Strong ChIP shows steep rise; flat diagonal indicates poor enrichment}
\li{\strong{Coverage}: Assess if sequencing depth is adequate for analysis}
}

\p{Full workflow details in \code{\startverb references/workflows.md\stopverb} → "ChIP-seq Quality Control Workflow"}
}

\subtree{
\title{ChIP-seq Complete Analysis Workflow}
\p{For full ChIP-seq analysis from BAM to visualizations:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Generate coverage tracks} with normalization (bamCoverage)}
\li{\strong{Create comparison tracks} (bamCompare for log2 ratio)}
\li{\strong{Compute signal matrices} around features (computeMatrix)}
\li{\strong{Generate visualizations} (plotHeatmap, plotProfile)}
\li{\strong{Enrichment analysis} at peaks (plotEnrichment)}
}

\p{Use \code{\startverb scripts/workflow_generator.py chipseq_analysis\stopverb} to generate template.}

\p{Complete command sequences in \code{\startverb references/workflows.md\stopverb} → "ChIP-seq Analysis Workflow"}
}

\subtree{
\title{RNA-seq Coverage Workflow}
\p{For strand-specific RNA-seq coverage tracks:}

\p{Use bamCoverage with \code{\startverb --filterRNAstrand\stopverb} to separate forward and reverse strands.}

\p{\strong{Important:} NEVER use \code{\startverb --extendReads\stopverb} for RNA-seq (would extend over splice junctions).}

\p{Use normalization: CPM for fixed bins, RPKM for gene-level analysis.}

\p{Template available: \code{\startverb scripts/workflow_generator.py rnaseq_coverage\stopverb}}

\p{Details in \code{\startverb references/workflows.md\stopverb} → "RNA-seq Coverage Workflow"}
}

\subtree{
\title{ATAC-seq Analysis Workflow}
\p{ATAC-seq requires Tn5 offset correction:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Shift reads} using alignmentSieve with \code{\startverb --ATACshift\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Generate coverage} with bamCoverage}
\li{\strong{Analyze fragment sizes} (expect nucleosome ladder pattern)}
\li{\strong{Visualize at peaks} if available}
}

\p{Template: \code{\startverb scripts/workflow_generator.py atacseq\stopverb}}

\p{Full workflow in \code{\startverb references/workflows.md\stopverb} → "ATAC-seq Workflow"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tool Categories and Common Tasks}
\subtree{
\title{BAM/bigWig Processing}
\p{\strong{Convert BAM to normalized coverage:}}

\pre{\startverb
bamCoverage --bam input.bam --outFileName output.bw \
    --normalizeUsing RPGC --effectiveGenomeSize 2913022398 \
    --binSize 10 --numberOfProcessors 8
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Compare two samples (log2 ratio):}}

\pre{\startverb
bamCompare -b1 treatment.bam -b2 control.bam -o ratio.bw \
    --operation log2 --scaleFactorsMethod readCount
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key tools:} bamCoverage, bamCompare, multiBamSummary, multiBigwigSummary, correctGCBias, alignmentSieve}

\p{Complete reference: \code{\startverb references/tools_reference.md\stopverb} → "BAM and bigWig File Processing Tools"}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quality Control}
\p{\strong{Check ChIP enrichment:}}

\pre{\startverb
plotFingerprint -b input.bam chip.bam -o fingerprint.png \
    --extendReads 200 --ignoreDuplicates
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Sample correlation:}}

\pre{\startverb
multiBamSummary bins --bamfiles *.bam -o counts.npz
plotCorrelation -in counts.npz --corMethod pearson \
    --whatToShow heatmap -o correlation.png
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key tools:} plotFingerprint, plotCoverage, plotCorrelation, plotPCA, bamPEFragmentSize}

\p{Complete reference: \code{\startverb references/tools_reference.md\stopverb} → "Quality Control Tools"}
}

\subtree{
\title{Visualization}
\p{\strong{Create heatmap around TSS:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Compute matrix
computeMatrix reference-point -S signal.bw -R genes.bed \
    -b 3000 -a 3000 --referencePoint TSS -o matrix.gz

# Generate heatmap
plotHeatmap -m matrix.gz -o heatmap.png \
    --colorMap RdBu --kmeans 3
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Create profile plot:}}

\pre{\startverb
plotProfile -m matrix.gz -o profile.png \
    --plotType lines --colors blue red
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key tools:} computeMatrix, plotHeatmap, plotProfile, plotEnrichment}

\p{Complete reference: \code{\startverb references/tools_reference.md\stopverb} → "Visualization Tools"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Normalization Methods}
\p{Choosing the correct normalization is critical for valid comparisons. Consult \code{\startverb references/normalization_methods.md\stopverb} for comprehensive guidance.}

\p{\strong{Quick selection guide:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{ChIP-seq coverage}: Use RPGC or CPM}
\li{\strong{ChIP-seq comparison}: Use bamCompare with log2 and readCount}
\li{\strong{RNA-seq bins}: Use CPM}
\li{\strong{RNA-seq genes}: Use RPKM (accounts for gene length)}
\li{\strong{ATAC-seq}: Use RPGC or CPM}
}

\p{\strong{Normalization methods:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{RPGC}: 1× genome coverage (requires --effectiveGenomeSize)}
\li{\strong{CPM}: Counts per million mapped reads}
\li{\strong{RPKM}: Reads per kb per million (accounts for region length)}
\li{\strong{BPM}: Bins per million}
\li{\strong{None}: Raw counts (not recommended for comparisons)}
}

\p{Full explanation: \code{\startverb references/normalization_methods.md\stopverb}}
}

\subtree{
\title{Effective Genome Sizes}
\p{RPGC normalization requires effective genome size. Common values:}

\pre{\startverb
| Organism | Assembly | Size | Usage |
|----------|----------|------|-------|
| Human | GRCh38/hg38 | 2,913,022,398 | `--effectiveGenomeSize 2913022398` |
| Mouse | GRCm38/mm10 | 2,652,783,500 | `--effectiveGenomeSize 2652783500` |
| Zebrafish | GRCz11 | 1,368,780,147 | `--effectiveGenomeSize 1368780147` |
| *Drosophila* | dm6 | 142,573,017 | `--effectiveGenomeSize 142573017` |
| *C. elegans* | ce10/ce11 | 100,286,401 | `--effectiveGenomeSize 100286401` |
\stopverb}

\p{Complete table with read-length-specific values: \code{\startverb references/effective_genome_sizes.md\stopverb}}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Parameters Across Tools}
\p{Many deepTools commands share these options:}

\p{\strong{Performance:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb --numberOfProcessors, -p\stopverb}: Enable parallel processing (always use available cores)}
\li{\code{\startverb --region\stopverb}: Process specific regions for testing (e.g., \code{\startverb chr1:1-1000000\stopverb})}
}

\p{\strong{Read Filtering:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb --ignoreDuplicates\stopverb}: Remove PCR duplicates (recommended for most analyses)}
\li{\code{\startverb --minMappingQuality\stopverb}: Filter by alignment quality (e.g., \code{\startverb --minMappingQuality 10\stopverb})}
\li{\code{\startverb --minFragmentLength\stopverb} / \code{\startverb --maxFragmentLength\stopverb}: Fragment length bounds}
\li{\code{\startverb --samFlagInclude\stopverb} / \code{\startverb --samFlagExclude\stopverb}: SAM flag filtering}
}

\p{\strong{Read Processing:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb --extendReads\stopverb}: Extend to fragment length (ChIP-seq: YES, RNA-seq: NO)}
\li{\code{\startverb --centerReads\stopverb}: Center at fragment midpoint for sharper signals}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\subtree{
\title{File Validation}
\p{\strong{Always validate files first} using \code{\startverb scripts/validate_files.py\stopverb} to check:}

\ul{
\li{File existence and readability}
\li{BAM indices present (.bai files)}
\li{BED format correctness}
\li{File sizes reasonable}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Analysis Strategy}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Start with QC}: Run correlation, coverage, and fingerprint analysis before proceeding}
\li{\strong{Test on small regions}: Use \code{\startverb --region chr1:1-10000000\stopverb} for parameter testing}
\li{\strong{Document commands}: Save full command lines for reproducibility}
\li{\strong{Use consistent normalization}: Apply same method across samples in comparisons}
\li{\strong{Verify genome assembly}: Ensure BAM and BED files use matching genome builds}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{ChIP-seq Specific}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Always extend reads} for ChIP-seq: \code{\startverb --extendReads 200\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Remove duplicates}: Use \code{\startverb --ignoreDuplicates\stopverb} in most cases}
\li{\strong{Check enrichment first}: Run plotFingerprint before detailed analysis}
\li{\strong{GC correction}: Only apply if significant bias detected; never use \code{\startverb --ignoreDuplicates\stopverb} after GC correction}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{RNA-seq Specific}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Never extend reads} for RNA-seq (would span splice junctions)}
\li{\strong{Strand-specific}: Use \code{\startverb --filterRNAstrand forward/reverse\stopverb} for stranded libraries}
\li{\strong{Normalization}: CPM for bins, RPKM for genes}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{ATAC-seq Specific}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Apply Tn5 correction}: Use alignmentSieve with \code{\startverb --ATACshift\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Fragment filtering}: Set appropriate min/max fragment lengths}
\li{\strong{Check nucleosome pattern}: Fragment size plot should show ladder pattern}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Performance Optimization}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Use multiple processors}: \code{\startverb --numberOfProcessors 8\stopverb} (or available cores)}
\li{\strong{Increase bin size} for faster processing and smaller files}
\li{\strong{Process chromosomes separately} for memory-limited systems}
\li{\strong{Pre-filter BAM files} using alignmentSieve to create reusable filtered files}
\li{\strong{Use bigWig over bedGraph}: Compressed and faster to process}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\subtree{
\title{Common Issues}
\p{\strong{BAM index missing:}}

\pre{\startverb
samtools index input.bam
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Out of memory:} Process chromosomes individually using \code{\startverb --region\stopverb}:}

\pre{\startverb
bamCoverage --bam input.bam -o chr1.bw --region chr1
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Slow processing:} Increase \code{\startverb --numberOfProcessors\stopverb} and/or increase \code{\startverb --binSize\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{bigWig files too large:} Increase bin size: \code{\startverb --binSize 50\stopverb} or larger}
}

\subtree{
\title{Validation Errors}
\p{Run validation script to identify issues:}

\pre{\startverb
python scripts/validate_files.py --bam *.bam --bed regions.bed
\stopverb}

\p{Common errors and solutions explained in script output.}
}
}

